data.content:
All three files are updated. Here's a summary of **every breaking change** identified and the fixes applied:

---

### Breaking changes fixed in this project

| # | Breaking Change | File | Fix |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | **TFM & packages** — must target `net9.0` and EF Core 9.0.0 | `EfApp.csproj` | Updated TFM and both package versions |
| 2 | **`Migrate()` inside user transaction throws** — EF Core 9 manages its own transactions internally | `MigrationRunner.cs` | Removed `BeginTransaction()`/`Commit()` wrapper; `Migrate()` is called directly inside the execution strategy |
| 3 | **`DateTime.UtcNow` in `HasData`** — produces non-deterministic seed data, generating spurious migrations on every snapshot comparison | `AppDbContext.cs` | Replaced with a fixed `DateTime` constant |

---

### Breaking changes for your Cosmos DB project (separate project)

**4. Discriminator property renamed `"Discriminator"` → `"$type"`**
EF Core 9 changed the default. Existing documents use `"Discriminator"`, so you must pin the old name:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<MyEntity>().HasDiscriminator<string>("Discriminator");
// Or globally for all entities:
modelBuilder.HasDiscriminator<string>("Discriminator");
```

Without this, EF Core 9 will look for `"$type"` in your existing documents and fail to materialize them.

**5. Synchronous Cosmos DB queries removed**
EF Core 9's Cosmos provider throws `InvalidOperationException` on sync I/O. Replace all sync calls:

```csharp
// Before (throws in EF 9):
var orders = db.Orders.ToList();
var first  = db.Orders.First(o => o.Id == 1);

// After:
var orders = await db.Orders.ToListAsync();
var first  = await db.Orders.FirstAsync(o => o.Id == 1);
```

This applies to `ToList`, `First`, `Single`, `Count`, `Any`, and all other LINQ terminal operators — use their `*Async` counterparts.
